<br>
My advice is to learn as much as you can about grouping and what should, and should not be done, as well as learn to communicate and organize a group. A druid who is pulling and not snare pulling (along with harmonizing) isn't doing his job, and obviously there was too much pulling since your cleric was oom all the time. I guess I'm a little harder on group members now that I've played nearly a year and played a lot of characters. I would be group leader and I would expect people to know their role but if they all wanted to do whatever without respecting the group then I would let each person know their role in the group. If they didn't want to listen they would be replaced. In CB it's far too easy to get new group members, and many will be experienced players playing alts.<br>
<br>
Some will agree with this approach and some will disagree, I've played with some players who wouldn't even warn other people before kicking them out; either they listened the first time or start lfg. In one case we were a mid-twenties group and the group leader announced that the monk, me, would pull. When a bard decided to do his own pulling he almost got us killed and was immediately dropped without explaination. In the end it's much like real war, discipline saves lives. It's a lot more fun to live and have everyone work together than have everyone do whatever they feel like and get everyone killed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/uzinj.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zinj</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 2790<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(5/29/02 9:56:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1543.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help..I keep dying :\</span><hr size=1> You're doing just fine.<br>
<br>
You're expected to be able to take on a blue conned mob solo and end up with a bubble or so of health ON THE AVERAGE.<br>
<br>
What's that mean?  It means sometimes you get lucky and land almost all your hits for close to maximum damage; and your opponent can't hit the broad side of the Freeport wall and only gives love taps.  It also means that sometimes you get your butt handed to you (at least until you hit 17 and train FD to 50 or more).<br>
<br>
Solution? <br>
Group.  <br>
If you stick to soloing, con every mob before attacking. <br>
Maximize your Bind Wounds skill, <br>
and carry several stacks of bandages at all times.  <br>
Work that mend button every time it pops up until it's maximized; then use it as soon as you drop to 75% health.<br>
Fight near a reachable zone line, and run for it before you get too low in health (you crawl if hurt too badly)<br>
Scan all around (F9 key) during fights to make sure nothing is sneaking up on you.  Adds are deadly!<br>
<br>
Zinj <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/usykeauttic.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syke Auttic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 402<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(5/29/02 12:12:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1543.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nwassociates.com/misc/everquest/SYKE_IVAN.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help..I keep dying :\</span><hr size=1> Unfortunately, you will find the same kind of "bad play" at higher levels too.  The issues you mentioned may be due to actual newbies who have do not understand how to play their class (ie druid not snaring and cleric oom due to nuking or possibly over-healing/healing more than the other cleric, etc).  I can't tell you how many times in the last 3 years I have heard horror stories about given zones or players...or frankly seen it for myself.<br>
<br>
There are just those out there that either cannot play their class because they are ignorant, negligent, or frankly arrogant enough to believe that they KNOW the right way to do things.  Just roll with it.  Learn to play YOUR characters as best you can...coming here is a good step in the right direction.  If YOU become good at playing a monk, others will notice and you will eventually end up playing with better players.  It just takes a little time... <p><br><br><CENTER>
